\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q8)
\series default
: Review the definition of uniform continuity.
 Given a differentiable function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to\R$
\end_inset

, let's say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is uniformly differentiable on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if, given 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(y\right)}{x-y}-f'\left(y\right)}<\epsilon\quad\text{whenever }0<\abs{x-y}<\delta.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Is 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 uniformly differentiable on 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

? How about 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=x^{3}$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

, then given an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\epsilon$
\end_inset

 such that whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\abs{x-y}<\delta$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\abs{\frac{x^{2}-y^{2}}{x-y}-2y} & =\abs{\frac{\left(x+y\right)\left(x-y\right)}{x-y}-2y}\\
 & =\abs{x-y}\\
 & <\delta\\
 & =\epsilon,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is uniformly differentiable on 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=x^{3}$
\end_inset

, then given an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=?$
\end_inset

 such that whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\abs{x-y}<\delta$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\abs{\frac{x^{3}-y^{3}}{x-y}-3y^{2}} & =\abs{\frac{\left(x-y\right)\left(x^{2}+xy+y^{2}\right)}{x-y}-3y^{2}}\\
 & =\abs{x^{2}+xy-2y^{2}}\\
 & =\abs{\left(x-y\right)\left(x+2y\right)},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since the domain is not bounded, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 will be a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Thus it is not uniformly differentiable on 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that if a function is uniformly differentiable on an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then the derivative must be continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We assume directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is uniformly differentiable on an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then given an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{x-y}<\delta$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(y\right)}{x-y}-f'\left(y\right)}<\epsilon/2.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\abs{f'\left(x\right)-f'\left(y\right)} & =\abs{f'\left(x\right)-\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(y\right)}{x-y}+\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(y\right)}{x-y}-f'\left(y\right)}\\
 & \leq\abs{f'\left(x\right)-\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(y\right)}{x-y}}+\abs{\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(y\right)}{x-y}-f'\left(y\right)}\\
 & <\frac{\epsilon}{2}+\frac{\epsilon}{2}\\
 & <\epsilon,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

thus the derivative is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Is there a theorem analogous to Theorem 4.4.7 for differentiation? Are functions
 that are differentiable on a closed interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 necessarily uniformly differentiable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Disproof
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We want to show by example that functions that are differentiable on a
 closed interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 are not necessarily uniformly differentiable.
 Since uniformly differentiable implies that the derivative is continuous,
 we just need to find a function whose derivative exists on the interval
 but is not continuous.
 Using the findings from exercise 
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
x^{2}\sin\left(1/x\right) & \text{if \ensuremath{x\neq0}}\\
0 & \text{else}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

be defined on the closed interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[-2,2\right]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is differentiable, but the derivative is not continuous.
 Hence the statement is false.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise

