\begin_inset Formula $g\left(y\right)<g\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
By definition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g'\left(a\right)=\lim_{x\to a}\frac{g\left(x\right)-g\left(a\right)}{x-a}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\left(a\right)<0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{x\to a}\frac{g\left(x\right)-g\left(a\right)}{x-a}<0.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x>a$
\end_inset

, the denominator must be positive.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)<g\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to a$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 arbitrarily close to 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(a\right)>g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The proof is similar to show that there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(y\right)<g\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
