Now complete the proof of Darboux's Theorem started earlier.
 (The first part of the proof is taken from the book)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We first simplify matters by defining a new function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=f\left(x\right)-\alpha x$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is differentiable on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\left(x\right)=f'\left(x\right)-\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, our hypothesis states that 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\left(a\right)<0<g'\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

, and we hope to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\left(c\right)=0$
\end_inset

