 Let's add the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\left(x\right)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is differentiable with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(f^{-1}\right)'\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{f'\left(x\right)}\quad\text{where }y=f\left(x\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Using the definition of the derivative
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(f^{-1}\right)'=\lim_{z\to y}\frac{f^{-1}\left(z\right)-f^{-1}\left(y\right)}{z-y},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in f\left(\left[a,b\right]\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This is possible since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\left[a,b\right]\right)$
\end_inset

 is a closed interval.
 Then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(k\right)=z$
\end_inset

.
 Using this we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim_{z\to y}\frac{f^{-1}\left(z\right)-f^{-1}\left(y\right)}{z-y} & =\lim_{k\to x}\frac{f^{-1}\left(f\left(k\right)\right)-f^{-1}\left(f\left(x\right)\right)}{f\left(k\right)-f\left(x\right)}\\
 & =\lim_{k\to x}\frac{k-x}{f\left(k\right)-f\left(x\right)}\\
 & =\frac{1}{f'\left(x\right)}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

